## Example A.5

Improper rational functions are often encountered in the analysis of discrete-time systems. To illustrate this, and also to show how they can be analyzed using the techniques developed here, consider the causal LTI system characterized by the difference equation

\[y[n]+\frac{5}{6}y[n-1]+\frac{1}{6}y[n-2]\,=\,x[n]+3x[n-1]+\frac{11}{6}\,x[n-2]+ \frac{1}{3}\,x[n-3].\]

The frequency response of this system is

\[H(e^{j\omega})\,=\,\frac{1+3e^{-j\omega}\,+\,\frac{11}{6}\,e^{-j2\omega}\,+\, \frac{1}{3}\,e^{-j3\omega}}{1+\,\frac{5}{6}e^{-j\omega}+\,\frac{1}{6}e^{-j2 \omega}}.\] (A.79)

Substituting \(v\) for \(e^{-j\omega}\), we obtain

\[G(v)\,=\,\frac{1+3v+\frac{11}{6}v^{2}+\frac{1}{3}v^{3}}{1+\frac{5}{6}v+\frac{ 1}{6}v^{2}}.\] (A.80)

This rational function can be written as the sum of a polynomial and a proper rational function:

\[G(v)\,=\,c_{0}+c_{1}v+\frac{b_{1}v+b_{0}}{1+\frac{5}{6}v+\frac{1}{6}v^{2}}.\] (A.81)

Equating eqs. (A.80) and (A.81), and multiplying by \(1+\frac{5}{6}v+\frac{1}{6}v^{2}\), we obtain

\[\begin{split} 1\,+\,3v\,+\,\frac{11}{6}v^{2}\,+\,\frac{1}{3}v^{3}\,=& \,(c_{0}+b_{0})+\bigg{(}\frac{5}{6}c_{0}+c_{1}+b_{1}\bigg{)}v\\ &+\bigg{(}\frac{1}{6}c_{0}+\frac{5}{6}c_{1}\bigg{)}v^{2}\,+\, \frac{1}{6}c_{1}v^{3}.\end{split}\] (A.82)

Equating coefficients, we see that

\[\begin{split}\frac{1}{6}c_{1}\,=\,\frac{1}{3}\,\to\,c_{1}\,=\,2, \\ \frac{1}{6}c_{0}+\frac{5}{6}c_{1}\,=\,\frac{11}{6}\,\to\,c_{0}\,=\,1,\\ \frac{5}{6}c_{0}+c_{1}+b_{1}\,=\,3\,\to\,b_{1}\,=\,\frac{1}{6}, \\ c_{0}+b_{0}\,=\,1\,\to b_{0}\,=\,0.\end{split}\] (A.83)

